   =20
      Bonus caps
   =20
 =20

One of the many things that people blamed for the 2008 financial crisis was=
 bank bonuses. The idea was that a lot of bankers and traders at investment=
 banks got most of their pay in the form of variable year-end bonuses, so t=
hey would take a lot of risk in order to get a big bonus: If their risky be=
ts worked out, they=E2=80=99d share in the gains (in the form of a bonus), =
but if they went bust they wouldn=E2=80=99t bear the losses. If they were i=
nstead paid mostly in salary, their risk-taking would have less upside (if =
they made a lot of money for the firm, they wouldn=E2=80=99t see much of it=
) and more downside (if they lost a lot of money for the firm, they=E2=80=
=99d be fired and lose their large recurring salary). I=E2=80=99m not sure =
this analysis was ever=C2=A0that=C2=A0compelling =E2=80=94=C2=A0even withou=
t a year-end bonus it seems like a good career move to make a lot of money =
for your firm,=C2=A0and=20
also to=20
lose a lot of=20
money=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it was widely believed, and the European Unio=
n ultimately  adopted rules limiting some bank employees=E2=80=99 bonuses t=
o two times their salary.
In theory this rule should make banks=E2=80=99=C2=A0behavior=C2=A0less risk=
y =E2=80=94=C2=A0all the bankers and traders will be less inclined to make =
big bets, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it also makes their=C2=A0finances=C2=A0mo=
re risky: One advantage of paying employees mostly in bonus is that you=C2=
=A0pay them a lot in good years and=C2=A0less in bad years. The EU bonus ca=
p led to much higher banking=C2=A0salaries=C2=A0(and lower bonuses), which =
means that banks have to pay employees more in bad years than they would ha=
ve under the old rules.
  [1]
=C2=A0In bad years, you want to have the flexibility to reduce your expense=
s.
But then the UK left the EU, which means it is no longer obligated to have =
a bonus cap, and   today it got rid of it:

The UK is going ahead with scrapping the cap on bankers=E2=80=99 bonuses, e=
nforcing plans unveiled by Liz Truss=E2=80=99s government last year.
The cap limiting bonuses to a maximum of twice a banker=E2=80=99s base pay =
will be lifted from October 31, the Prudential Regulation Authority said on=
 Tuesday.
Banks can pay staff as they like for the current financial year, the PRA sa=
id, though they need to ensure fixed and variable pay are =E2=80=9Cappropri=
ately balanced.=E2=80=9D
The European Union introduced the bonus cap for =E2=80=9Cmaterial risk take=
rs=E2=80=9D in 2014 in response to public fury about the financial crisis. =
The UK unsuccessfully opposed the measure, on the grounds it would prompt f=
irms to hike fixed pay, making it harder to manage costs.

Here is  the PRA=E2=80=99s final policy statement. Here is the original  co=
nsultation paper from December, which argues that paying bankers more in bo=
nus is good for the bank=E2=80=99s financial stability:
The removal of the bonus cap would be expected to make it easier for firms =
to adjust their variable remuneration through time to reflect their financi=
al health. By adjusting down variable pay in the event of a downturn, firms=
 would have more resources that could be used to absorb losses, thereby pro=
moting the safety and soundness and long-term viability of the firm.
And also that it will actually reduce bankers=E2=80=99 risk-taking, because=
 bonuses are subject to deferral and clawbacks while base salary is not:

From an incentive-setting perspective, the wider remuneration regime primar=
ily applies to the variable component of pay, and so removing regulatory co=
nstraints on maximum levels of variable pay would allow for a larger propor=
tion of total pay to be subject to the other remuneration policy requiremen=
ts that were introduced after the financial crisis. These rules =E2=80=93 w=
hich will remain in place under the regulators=E2=80=99 proposals =E2=80=93=
 aim to better align remuneration with prudent risk taking, by shaping the =
nature of incentives and ensuring accountability. =E2=80=A6
The combination of deferral and risk adjustment tools aim to disincentivise=
 individuals from taking excessive risk to achieve a high return in the sho=
rt-run without due consideration for the long-term consequences. In additio=
n, by deferring the payment (or =E2=80=98vesting=E2=80=99) of part of an aw=
ard, there is an opportunity to reassess the nature, scale, and outcomes of=
 the risks taken in order to assess the performance for which variable remu=
neration has been awarded. Linking a substantial proportion of variable rem=
uneration to the performance of the firm aims to align incentives of MRTs [=
material risk takers]=C2=A0with long-term value creation and interests of s=
hareholders (addressing the =E2=80=98principal-agent=E2=80=99 problem).

In the pre-2008 regime, if you got a bonus, you got to spend it, so you had=
 incentives to do things that made a lot of money in the short term but cre=
ated a lot of long-term risks. In the 2023 regime, if you get a bonus, a lo=
t of it gets deferred for years, and a lot of it is paid in stock, and it c=
an be clawed back if things go wrong: Taking long-term risks for short-term=
 gains won=E2=80=99t help you, because you=E2=80=99ll be awarded a big bonu=
s now but it=E2=80=99ll be worthless by the time it is actually paid. Where=
as if you get a big=C2=A0salary, you still get to spend it. So paying highe=
r bonuses and lower salaries incentivizes=C2=A0less=C2=A0recklessness. Or t=
hat=E2=80=99s the idea.
I suppose the question now is whether=C2=A0banks will actually cut base sal=
aries for UK employees? And make up for it with higher bonuses? (Or not, if=
 they have a bad year.) One possibility is that the last decade and a half =
of post-crisis regulation has had the intended effect of changing the cultu=
re of big investment banks, such that everyone who currently works at the b=
ig banks is conservative and risk-averse and wants a big steady salary rath=
er than a lot of upside.
Another possibility is that, sure, the people who work there=C2=A0now=C2=A0=
are risk-averse and want to get paid mostly base=C2=A0salary, but what abou=
t the new hires?  The Financial Times reports:

Anne Sammon, partner at law firm Pinsent Masons, said there was a =E2=80=9C=
risk associated with creating a two-tier workforce where new employees are =
paid lower salaries but with higher bonus potential=E2=80=9D.
=E2=80=9CThose who received increases to fixed pay when the bonus cap was i=
ntroduced will be contractually entitled to those higher salaries and so wi=
ll only give those up where they are offered some incentive to do so,=E2=80=
=9D she added.

I don=E2=80=99t really believe that big banks in the UK will implement a tw=
o-tier workforce, in which the people who work there already will get big b=
ase salaries and lower bonuses, while new hires get lower salaries and high=
er bonuses. But wouldn=E2=80=99t that be a cool experiment? Like:
=09Everyone who wants a high base salary stays where they are. They are rel=
atively senior people, so the senior management at each bank will be conser=
vative, both by temperament and by incentives.=09Everybody who wants to eat=
 what they kill can just switch jobs. The new hires at each bank will, by t=
emperament and by incentives, be the risk-takers.=09The new analysts hired =
right out of university will be back on the old mostly-bonus track.=C2=A0No=
w=C2=A0they will be too junior to (1) get a huge bonus or (2) take that man=
y risks with the firm=E2=80=99s money, but give them time.=C2=A0

And then, I don=E2=80=99t know, see what happens? Maybe the PRA is right th=
at the new bonus rules make bonuses the=C2=A0less=C2=A0risky choice, and al=
l the people who get paid mostly in bonus end up being more careful long-te=
rm stewards of their banks=E2=80=99 capital, while the people who get paid =
mostly in salary pay less attention to risk.=C2=A0
You can see why, after 2008, politicians and regulators wanted banks to tak=
e less risk. But discouraging bankers from being risk-takers has some bad c=
onsequences. Banks are fundamentally=C2=A0risky: They are leveraged busines=
ses, they borrow short to lend long, there is always some risk of blowing u=
p. Silicon Valley Bank failed this year because it bought too many Treasury=
 bonds; surely it didn=E2=80=99t intend=C2=A0that to be a big risk. If you =
get rid of all the risk-takers at a bank, then there will be no one left wh=
o is good at taking risks,=C2=A0but the bank will still be taking risks. Yo=
u have to strike the right balance.=C2=A0Maybe the new regime does that: Pa=
ying big bonuses attracts risk takers, but paying big deferred bonuses attr=
acts thoughtful, long-term risk-takers.

