   =20
      DAOs
   =20
 =20

The normal way for a venture capital firm to invest in a startup company is=
 something like this. The startup is a=C2=A0corporation, and it issues=C2=
=A0stock, and the VC firm (through one of its funds) buys the stock. The VC=
 firm might get a seat on the startup=E2=80=99s board of directors, and mig=
ht have some say in running the startup. But the startup is a separate comp=
any. If it is doing bad stuff, the VC firm could lose the money it invested=
 in the startup, but it will not ordinarily get in trouble for the startup=
=E2=80=99s actions. When startups like Theranos and FTX collapsed in scanda=
l, the VC firms that bought their stock were treated as=C2=A0victims=C2=A0o=
f the scandals, not=C2=A0co-conspirators.=C2=A0
And then the way the VC firm makes money is by eventually selling their sto=
ck, when the startup goes public or is bought by a bigger company.
In the crypto boom, VC firms discovered a different way to invest in startu=
ps. The startup would be a=C2=A0crypto project, and it would issue=C2=A0tok=
ens, and the VC firm would buy the tokens. The tokens might have some gover=
nance rights: The crypto project might be a DAO, a decentralized autonomous=
 organization, whose token holders get to vote on what it should do.=C2=A0
The advantages of this structure, for VCs, were:=C2=A0
=09Crypto tokens, DAOs, web3, etc.=C2=A0got a lot of hype, so in 2021 you c=
ould buy these tokens and resell them for more of a profit than you might g=
et by investing in normal stock in normal startups.=09You could sell=C2=A0f=
aster:=C2=A0Crypto tokens lived, or seemed to live, in a weird regulatory g=
ray area, so you could buy the crypto project=E2=80=99s tokens, say to your=
self =E2=80=9Cahhh these tokens are not=C2=A0securities, =09=09they are =E2=
=80=98little more than alphanumeric cryptographic sequences,=E2=80=99=E2=80=
=9D and=C2=A0sell them to retail investors on some crypto exchange.=C2=A0In=
stead of buying stock and waiting for years for a startup to be successful =
enough to do an initial public offering, you could buy tokens and flip them=
 quickly while the hype was strong.

I don=E2=80=99t mean to overstate this; many well-lawyered VC firms=C2=A0di=
dn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0go around blindly flipping tokens to retail investors, be=
cause they worried about the risk that those tokens would be classified as =
securities. Certainly the US Securities and Exchange Commission   thinks th=
ey are   all securities. I have   argued that   these tokens are, in many c=
ases,=C2=A0functionally stock, and thus obviously securities.
But there is another problem with the token approach, which is that, while =
these tokens might be functionally stock, and while the SEC thinks (and   c=
ourts might agree) that they are therefore securities, they are not literal=
ly stock, and these crypto DAOs are not literally corporations. Specificall=
y, they are not=C2=A0incorporated. Nobody filed a form with the Delaware se=
cretary of state to incorporate the crypto DAO as a corporation. (This is n=
ot always true, and for instance Wyoming has a special statutory flavor of =
 DAO limited liability company, but it is=C2=A0often=C2=A0true.)
This seems like a small technicality, but one important benefit that you ge=
t, from filling out a form and paying a fee to incorporate a corporation, i=
s=C2=A0limited liability. If you have a business entity that is not incorpo=
rated, then it is often, by default, a general partnership. Which means tha=
t the investors who fund and participate in running it are, arguably, gener=
al partners. Shareholders of a corporation are not generally liable for the=
 corporation=E2=80=99s actions, but general partners of a partnership gener=
ally are. For instance, they might be liable for its unregistered sales of =
securities.
Or that is a theory. Late last year, some holders of Compound DAO=E2=80=99s=
 COMP tokens  sued the venture capitalists backing Compound for unregistere=
d securities sales. The idea is:
=09=E2=80=9CCompound is a business that allows users to borrow and lend cry=
pto assets, in much the same way that a traditional bank allows customers t=
o borrow and lend traditional currencies.=E2=80=9D It is a big player in de=
centralized finance, letting people borrow and lend using smart contracts r=
ather than centralized intermediaries.=09Compound is governed by a DAO, and=
 =E2=80=9CCompound DAO is governed by the holders of a security called COMP=
.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=09Compound issued some COMP tokens to its early investors =
and founders. It issues others to people who use the Compound smart-contrac=
t protocol: If you deposit or borrow on Compound, you can earn COMP tokens.=
 (=E2=80=9CThis is an example of a strategy called =E2=80=98yield farming=
=E2=80=99 or =E2=80=98liquidity mining,=E2=80=99 which Compound essentially=
 pioneered,=E2=80=9D says the complaint. We have =09=09talked about yield f=
arming before.)=09COMP trades publicly on crypto exchanges: If you use Comp=
ound and get some tokens, you can sell them for cash, and people do.=09=E2=
=80=9CNine people control at least 51.56% of the COMP currently issued,=E2=
=80=9D including the co-founders of Compound and venture capital firms incl=
uding Bain Capital Ventures, Polychain Alchemy, Andreessen Horowitz and Par=
adigm.=09Those people and firms are=C2=A0general partners=C2=A0of Compound,=
 liable for any bad stuff that it does.=09One arguably bad thing that Compo=
und does is list the COMP token on crypto exchanges, where people can buy i=
t.=C2=A0=09The plaintiffs in this case bought some COMP on the exchanges =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0not=C2=A0from Compound or its venture investors =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and are now suing, arguing that this was an unregistered sale of securit=
ies and that=C2=A0the venture capitalists are responsible for it.

The VCs moved to dismiss the complaint, and last month a federal judge  den=
ied their request, finding =E2=80=9Cthat there are sufficient allegations a=
gainst each of the Partner Defendants to allow the Securities Act claim to =
go forward at this juncture.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CThe Partner Defendants have =
=E2=80=98reserved=E2=80=99 their right to contest whether Compound DAO is a=
 general partnership or whether any of them are general partners in that or=
 a related partnership,=E2=80=9D he wrote, but I guess it=E2=80=99s not a g=
reat sign, for them, that he calls them =E2=80=9Cthe Partner Defendants.=E2=
=80=9D
Also not great, from the complaint:
Retail COMP purchasers generally have not fared well. The value of COMP pea=
ked in May 2021 at nearly $500 per token, which created a total market capi=
talization of about $4 billion. It soon halved in value, and in the fall of=
 2021, COMP=E2=80=99s market capitalization was a little more than $2 billi=
on. In the year preceding the filing of this Action, COMP has fallen in val=
ue by another 90%. Its market capitalization is approximately $278 million.
If Compound was doing an unregistered sale of securities, then it could be =
liable for those investors=E2=80=99 losses. If Compound is just a pot of cr=
ypto in decentralized finance, then that liability might=C2=A0not be worth =
much. But if Compound is a general partnership, and its partners are big VC=
 firms, then=C2=A0they=C2=A0might be liable for the losses.
This theory is not unique to this case, and we   talked last year about a U=
S Commodity Futures Trading Commission action against a=C2=A0crypto thing c=
alled Ooki=C2=A0DAO, also arguing that its voting token holders could be ge=
neral partners. But after the crypto crash, if token holders can get their =
money back by suing the VCs behind crypto projects, we might see more of it=
.
I remember the days of crypto optimism in 2021. One thing that crypto enthu=
siasts and venture capitalists liked to say was that crypto was a new way o=
f organizing human economic behavior, that crypto would enable a new =E2=80=
=9CWeb3=E2=80=9D in which technology was organized collectively and belonge=
d to its users instead of being owned by big corporations. This could seem =
pretty cynical, as VC firms often owned big stakes in (the tokens of) these=
 web3 projects.=C2=A0
But also it was just a big factual mistake! Crypto and DAOs and web3 were n=
ot a new way of organizing human economic behavior;   they were an old way,=
 the general partnership. They were a technological step=C2=A0backward:=C2=
=A0Ages ago, lawyers and financiers and governments figured out a new way t=
o organize human behavior, the corporation, which allowed people to pool th=
eir capital in a new venture in ways that limited their risk and thus encou=
raged more and safer capital formation.=C2=A0And then crypto came along and=
 people=C2=A0forgot.

 =20
   =20
      Dimes
   =20
 =20

One thing that I=20
think about sometimes is what sorts of businesses, in what sorts of circums=
tances, have an obligation to catch and report money launderers. If you run=
 a deli and someone comes in and tries to buy a sandwich with a $20 bill, y=
ou will not think twice about it; that=E2=80=99s a normal transaction and n=
ot at all evidence of money laundering. If you run a real estate brokerage =
and someone comes in and tries to buy a Central Park South apartment with a=
 suitcase full of $100 bills, you might call a lawyer. Cash transactions ar=
e not in themselves suspicious, but at some size they start becoming suspic=
ious.
Similarly with coin=C2=A0transactions. If you run a supermarket with a Coin=
star machine and someone comes in with a jar of change to convert into bill=
s, fine. If some guys come=C2=A0in with a truck and a bucket and spend=C2=
=A0four hours patiently pouring dimes into the machine, at some point you a=
re going to call the police? You can only have  so many dimes for legitimat=
e reasons:

Four men have been charged in a $234,500 heist that saw the thieves swiping=
 more than 2 million dimes from a tractor-trailer hauling the coins from th=
e US Mint in Philadelphia earlier this year, according to The Philadelphia =
Inquirer. ...
In the weeks after the theft, thousands of the dimes were converted into ca=
sh at Coinstar machines in Maryland, and in at least four different banks a=
cross suburban Philadelphia, according to an indictment unsealed Friday obt=
ained by The Post.
However, the amount of laundered coins identified in the court documents ad=
ds up to roughly $5,200 =E2=80=94 a tiny fraction of what authorities say t=
he men stole.

Thousands of dimes! $5,200!  Fortune reports:

The indictment unsealed Friday offered some clues. The day after the theft,=
 it says, [defendant] Malik Palmer sent the others a link to an online calc=
ulator that can estimate the total cash value of a collection of coins base=
d on weight and denomination.
In the weeks after the theft, the others allegedly converted thousands of d=
ollars of dimes into cash at Coinstar machines in Maryland or by depositing=
 them in at least four different banks in suburban Philadelphia.

Here is one such  calculator, which tells me that $5,200 is 260 pounds of d=
imes. It just seems like an exhausting way to do crime.

