arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> adopted rules</a> limiting some bank em=
ployees=E2=80=99 bonuses to two times their salary.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In theory this rule should make banks=E2=80=99=
=C2=A0<em>behavior=C2=A0</em>less risky =E2=80=94=C2=A0all the bankers and =
traders will be less inclined to make big bets, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it =
also makes their=C2=A0<em>finances=C2=A0</em>more risky: One advantage of p=
aying employees mostly in bonus is that you=C2=A0pay them a lot in good yea=
rs and=C2=A0<em>less in bad years</em>. The EU bonus cap led to much higher=
 banking=C2=A0<em>salaries=C2=A0</em>(and lower bonuses), which means that =
banks have to pay employees more in bad years than they would have under th=
e old rules.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-=
color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0In bad years, you want to have the flexibility to reduce your exp=
enses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then the UK left the EU, which means it is=
 no longer obligated to have a bonus cap, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/33130424.259419/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMjQvdWstdG8tc2NyYXAtYmFua2Vycy1ib251cy1jYX=
AtaW4tY29tcGV0aXRpdmVuZXNzLXB1c2g_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAyNDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX=
21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMDI0JnV0bV9j=
YW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB92d5cdc3" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  today=
 it got rid of it</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The UK is going ahead with scrapping the cap o=
n bankers=E2=80=99 bonuses, enforcing plans unveiled by Liz Truss=E2=80=99s=
 government last year.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The cap limiting bonuses to a maximum of twice=
 a banker=E2=80=99s base pay will be lifted from October 31, the Prudential=
 Regulation Authority said on Tuesday.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Banks can pay staff as they like for the curre=
nt financial year, the PRA said, though they need to ensure fixed and varia=
ble pay are =E2=80=9Cappropriately balanced.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The European Union introduced the bonus cap fo=
r =E2=80=9Cmaterial risk takers=E2=80=9D in 2014 in response to public fury=
 about the financial crisis. The UK unsuccessfully opposed the measure, on =
the grounds it would prompt firms to hike fixed pay, making it harder to ma=
nage costs.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/33130424.259419/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmFua29mZW5nbGFuZC5jby51=
ay9wcnVkZW50aWFsLXJlZ3VsYXRpb24vcHVibGljYXRpb24vMjAyMy9vY3RvYmVyL3JlbXVuZXJ=
hdGlvbi1yYXRpby1iZXR3ZWVuLWZpeGVkLWFuZC12YXJpYWJsZS1jb21wb25lbnRzLW9mLXRvdG=
FsLXJlbXVuZXJhdGlvbg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf2f48d2f" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the PRA=E2=
=80=99s final policy statement</a>. Here is the original <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33130424.259419/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmFu=
a29mZW5nbGFuZC5jby51ay9wcnVkZW50aWFsLXJlZ3VsYXRpb24vcHVibGljYXRpb24vMjAyMi9=
kZWNlbWJlci9yZW11bmVyYXRpb24/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB61093aba" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> co=
nsultation paper</a> from December, which argues that paying bankers more i=
n bonus is good for the bank=E2=80=99s financial stability:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The removal of the bonus cap would=
 be expected to make it easier for firms to adjust their variable remunerat=
ion through time to reflect their financial health. By adjusting down varia=
ble pay in the event of a downturn, firms would have more resources that co=
uld be used to absorb losses, thereby promoting the safety and soundness an=
d long-term viability of the firm.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And also that it will actually reduce bankers=
=E2=80=99 risk-taking, because bonuses are subject to deferral and clawback=
s while base salary is not:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From an incentive-setting perspective, the wid=
er remuneration regime primarily applies to the variable component of pay, =
and so removing regulatory constraints on maximum levels of variable pay wo=
uld allow for a larger proportion of total pay to be subject to the other r=
emuneration policy requirements that were introduced after the financial cr=
isis. These rules =E2=80=93 which will remain in place under the regulators=
=E2=80=99 proposals =E2=80=93 aim to better align remuneration with prudent=
 risk taking, by shaping the nature of incentives and ensuring accountabili=
ty. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The combination of deferral and risk adjustmen=
t tools aim to disincentivise individuals from taking excessive risk to ach=
ieve a high return in the short-run without due consideration for the long-=
term consequences. In addition, by deferring the payment (or =E2=80=98vesti=
ng=E2=80=99) of part of an award, there is an opportunity to reassess the n=
ature, scale, and outcomes of the risks taken in order to assess the perfor=
mance for which variable remuneration has been awarded. Linking a substanti=
al proportion of variable remuneration to the performance of the firm aims =
to align incentives of MRTs [material risk takers]=C2=A0with long-term valu=
e creation and interests of shareholders (addressing the =E2=80=98principal=
-agent=E2=80=99 problem).</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the pre-2008 regime, if you got a bonus, yo=
u got to spend it, so you had incentives to do things that made a lot of mo=
ney in the short term but created a lot of long-term risks. In the 2023 reg=
ime, if you get a bonus, a lot of it gets deferred for years, and a lot of =
it is paid in stock, and it can be clawed back if things go wrong: Taking l=
ong-term risks for short-term gains won=E2=80=99t help you, because you=E2=
=80=99ll be awarded a big bonus now but it=E2=80=99ll be worthless by the t=
ime it is actually paid. Whereas if you get a big=C2=A0<em>salary</em>, you=
 still get to spend it. So paying higher bonuses and lower salaries incenti=
vizes=C2=A0<em>less=C2=A0</em>recklessness. Or that=E2=80=99s the idea.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose the question now is whether=C2=A0ban=
ks will actually cut base salaries for UK employees? And make up for it wit=
h higher bonuses? (Or not, if they have a bad year.) One possibility is tha=
t the last decade and a half of post-crisis regulation has had the intended=
 effect of changing the culture of big investment banks, such that everyone=
 who currently works at the big banks is conservative and risk-averse and w=
ants a big steady salary rather than a lot of upside.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another possibility is that, sure, the people =
who work there=C2=A0<em>now=C2=A0</em>are risk-averse and want to get paid =
mostly base=C2=A0salary, but what about the new hires? <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33130424.259419/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY2=
9tL2NvbnRlbnQvY2M0MTljYWYtMjEzZC00MThlLWI5MjEtOTBlODBjN2ExMTRi/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBca5b6aa7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> The Financial Times reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anne Sammon, partner at law firm Pinsent Mason=
s, said there was a =E2=80=9Crisk associated with creating a two-tier workf=
orce where new employees are paid lower salaries but with higher bonus pote=
ntial=E2=80=9D.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThose who received increases to fixed=
 pay when the bonus cap was introduced will be contractually entitled to th=
ose higher salaries and so will only give those up where they are offered s=
ome incentive to do so,=E2=80=9D she added.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t really believe that big banks =
in the UK will implement a two-tier workforce, in which the people who work=
 there already will get big base salaries and lower bonuses, while new hire=
s get lower salaries and higher bonuses. But wouldn=E2=80=99t that be a coo=
l experiment? Like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Everyone who wants a high base salary=
 stays where they are. They are relatively senior people, so the senior man=
agement at each bank will be conservative, both by temperament and by incen=
tives.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Everybody who wants to eat =
what they kill can just switch jobs. The new hires at each bank will, by te=
mperament and by incentives, be the risk-takers.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">The new analysts hired right out of university will be back =
on the old mostly-bonus track.=C2=A0<em>Now=C2=A0</em>they will be too juni=
or to (1) get a huge bonus or (2) take that many risks with the firm=E2=80=
=99s money, but give them time.=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then, I don=E2=80=99t know, see what happe=
ns? Maybe the PRA is right that the new bonus rules make bonuses the=C2=A0<=
em>less=C2=A0</em>risky choice, and all the people who get paid mostly in b=
onus end up being more careful long-term stewards of their banks=E2=80=99 c=
apital, while the people who get paid mostly in salary pay less attention t=
o risk.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can see why, after 2008, politicians and r=
egulators wanted banks to take less risk. But discouraging bankers from bei=
ng risk-takers has some bad consequences. Banks are <em>fundamentally=C2=A0=
</em>risky: They are leveraged businesses, they borrow short to lend long, =
there is always some risk of blowing up. Silicon Valley Bank failed this ye=
ar because it bought too many Treasury bonds; surely it didn=E2=80=99t <em>=
intend=C2=A0</em>that to be a big risk. If you get rid of all the risk-take=
rs at a bank, then there will be no one left who is good at taking risks,=
=C2=A0<em>but the bank will still be taking risks</em>. You have to strike =
the right balance.=C2=A0Maybe the new regime does that: Paying big bonuses =
attracts risk takers, but paying big <em>deferred </em>bonuses attracts tho=
ughtful, long-term risk-takers.</p>
